 early bearers without the definite article could alternatively belong with (2).","2  English:  see  Moon   (1)."],"variants":[{"name":"Moin","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of <b>Moyne</b>, a nickname from Old French <i>moine</i>, Anglo-Norman French <i>muine</i>, <i>moingne</i> ‘monk’.","Muslim (mainly the Indian subcontinent): unexplained."]},{"name":"Moon","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Mohan  .","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Moyon in La Manche. Compare   Mounce  .","Americanized form of German   Mohn   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"Moynan","meanings":["Irish: perhaps a diminutive of   Moyne   or a reduced form of   Moynihan  ."]},{"name":"Moine","meanings":["French: from <i>moine</i> ‘monk’, probably applied as an occupational name for a servant at a monastery or an ironic nickname for someone of monkish behavior or appearance. Compare   Lemoine  ."]},{"name":"Moynes","meanings":["English: variant of   Moyne   with post-medieval excrescent  <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":28,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed aroun